[[File:Cordelia E Cook 1943.jpg|thumb|Cook tending a wounded serviceman in 1943, showing her shrapnel wound, for which she received a [[Purple Heart]] award]]
'''Cordelia Elizabeth "Betty" Cook ''' (March 17, 1919 â€“ June 19, 1996) was an American [[Combat medic|combat nurse]] in the [[United States Army Nurse Corps]] during World War II. She was the first woman in the U.S. Army to receive both the [[Bronze Star Medal]] award and the [[Purple Heart]].

== Early life ==
Cook was born in [[Fort Thomas, Kentucky]], on March 17, 1919.{{sfn|Commire|Klezmer|2007|p=429}} She obtained her [[elementary school|primary schooling]] in Fort Thomas. Cook had three siblings (Navada b.1904, Henry b.1913, Jack b.1924).<ref>1930 U.S. Census, Fort Thomas, Campbell, Kentucky; Roll 738, page: 2B, Enumeration District 0034, Image 678.0 FHL 2340473. National Archives and Records Administration</ref> She went by the name "Betty".{{sfn|Frank|2013|p=161}}

== Military duty ==
Cook attended the Christ Hospital School of Nursing in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]], for 3 years and graduated in 1940.{{sfn|Frank|2013|p=161}} She became a surgical nurse with the rank of [[first lieutenant]] in the United States Army Nurse Corps.{{sfn|Read|Witlieb|1992|p=101}} Cook was sent to Europe during World War II. The [[field hospital]] in Italy she was working at was bombed in 1943.{{sfn|Baron|1998|p=68}}  In spite of the dangers, she continued her nursing duties into January 1944 at the 11th Field Hospital in the [[Presenzano]] sector at the [[Italian Campaign (World War II)|Italian front]].{{sfn|Loomis|1958|p=75}}  She received a Bronze Star Medal award for her service, being the first woman to receive the award.{{sfn|Kane|1964|p=358}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wwiimemorial.com/registry/search/pframe.asp?HonoreeID=2383494&popcount=1&tcount=1 |title= World War II Honoree |author= |year=2003 |website= National World War II Memorial  |publisher= American Battle Monuments Commission; National Archives and Records Administration |accessdate=30 January 2014}}</ref> Cook sustained a [[Shrapnel shell|shrapnel]] wound from German artillery fire while carrying out her duties.{{sfn|Commire|Klezmer|2007|p=429}}{{sfn|Baron|1998|p=68}} Because of this she received the Purple Heart award, becoming the first woman to receive both the Bronze Star Medal and Purple Heart awards.{{sfn|Baron|1998|p=68}}{{sfn|Kane|1964|p=358}}{{sfn|Robinson|1946|p=352}}{{sfn|Jackson|2006|p=58}}

== Personal life ==
Cook married Harold E. Fillmore, a U.S. Army captain.<ref>Note: The married name she used for documents and legal use was Cordelia Elizabeth Fillmore or Cordelia E. Fillmore.</ref>  The Fillmores had a daughter, Sara, and two sons, David and William.<ref name=CookObit/>  After the war, she worked as a registered nurse at Doctors Hospital North in [[Columbus, Ohio]], for 28 years. She was a member of the Crestview Presbyterian Church in [[West Chester Township, Butler County, Ohio|West Chester, Ohio]], near Cincinnati.<ref name=CookObit>''Columbus Dispatch'' newspaper (Columbus, Ohio) - Thursday, June 20, 1996 - obituary, p. 7F</ref>  Cook died in [[Upper Arlington, Ohio]], on June 19, 1996, at 77 years of age.<ref name=CookObit/>

